0:{"rsc":["$","$1","c",{"children":[["$","article",null,{"className":"mx-auto max-w-3xl px-5 sm:px-8 pt-16 sm:pt-24","children":[["$","script",null,{"type":"application/ld+json","dangerouslySetInnerHTML":{"__html":"{\"@context\":\"https://schema.org\",\"@type\":\"BlogPosting\",\"headline\":\"Why Everyday Policing Deserves More Attention\",\"description\":\"Dramatic reforms make headlines, but most encounters between citizens and the police happen in routine, unremarkable moments.\",\"datePublished\":\"2026-06-08\",\"image\":\"http://localhost:3000/portrait.webp\",\"url\":\"http://localhost:3000/blog/why-everyday-policing-deserves-more-attention\",\"author\":{\"@type\":\"Person\",\"name\":\"Zunera\",\"url\":\"http://localhost:3000\"},\"articleSection\":\"Policing\"}"}}],["$","$L2",null,{"children":["$","$L3",null,{"href":"/blog","className":"inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 text-sm text-ink-soft hover:text-accent transition-colors","children":[["$","$L4",null,{"iconNode":[["path",{"d":"m12 19-7-7 7-7","key":"1l729n"}],["path",{"d":"M19 12H5","key":"x3x0zl"}]],"className":"lucide-arrow-left","size":15}]," All posts"]}]}],["$","$L2",null,{"delay":0.08,"children":["$","div",null,{"className":"mt-6 flex items-center gap-3 text-xs text-ink-soft","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"rounded-full bg-accent-soft px-3 py-1 font-medium text-accent","children":"Policing"}],["$","time",null,{"dateTime":"2026-06-08","children":"8 June 2026"}]]}]}],["$","$L2",null,{"delay":0.14,"children":["$","h1",null,{"className":"mt-4 font-serif text-4xl sm:text-5xl tracking-tight leading-[1.1]","children":"Why Everyday Policing Deserves More Attention"}]}],"",["$","$L2",null,{"delay":0.22,"children":["$","div",null,{"className":"prose-z mt-9","dangerouslySetInnerHTML":{"__html":"<p>Public debate about policing tends to focus on dramatic moments: high-profile operations, scandals, and sweeping reform announcements.</p><p>Most policing, however, happens in routine encounters. A complaint filed at a station desk, a checkpoint conversation, a patrol through a familiar neighbourhood. These small moments shape how citizens experience the state far more than any headline.</p><p>Taking the everyday seriously changes the questions we ask. Instead of only asking whether a reform passed, we can ask how it lands in practice, who it reaches, and what informal routines grow around it.</p><p>Future posts will pick up specific examples from research in South Asian cities.</p>"}}]}]]}],[["$","script","script-0",{"src":"/_next/static/chunks/1c9sza45s9t7y.js","async":true}]],["$","$L5",null,{"children":["$","$6",null,{"name":"Next.MetadataOutlet","children":"$@7"}]}]]}],"isPartial":false,"staleTime":300,"varyParams":null,"buildId":"BP63z9ZV3VAYNCQwPAb1q"}
